\s2 The promise  
\p
\v 13 \w Now|strong="G1510"\w* \w the|strong="G1223"\w* \w promise|strong="G1860"\w* \w that|strong="G3588"\w* \w he|strong="G3588"\w* \w would|strong="G1510"\w* \w be|strong="G1510"\w* \w the|strong="G1223"\w* \w heir|strong="G2818"\w* \w of|strong="G1223"\w* \w the|strong="G1223"\w* \w world|strong="G2889"\w*\f + \fr 4:13 \ft Now what might ‘heir of the world’ mean? “In you all the families of the earth shall be blessed” (Genesis 12:3). Galatians 3:16 makes clear that the Seed, singular, refers to the Christ (Genesis 12:7 and 24:7). Psalm 2:7-8 also clearly refers to the Christ: “I will declare the decree: the Lord has said to Me, ‘You are My Son, today I have begotten You. Ask of Me, and I will give You the nations for your inheritance, and the ends of the earth for your possession.’ ” It might be argued that in some sense this is happening through the Church, Christ's body—in Matthew 5:13-14 the Christ called His disciples “the salt of the earth” and “the light of the world”. Paul states, “all things are yours… and you are Christ's… and Christ is God's” (1 Corinthians 3:21-23). But during the millennial Messianic Kingdom the whole world will obey the Christ, who will rule the nations with ‘a rod of iron’ (Revelation 19:15).\f* \w was|strong="G1510"\w* \w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w to|strong="G3756"\w* Abraham, \w or|strong="G2228"\w* \w his|strong="G1223"\w* \w seed|strong="G4690"\w*, \w through|strong="G1223"\w* \w law|strong="G3551"\w*, \w but|strong="G1063"\w* \w through|strong="G1223"\w* \w the|strong="G1223"\w* \w righteousness|strong="G1343"\w* \w of|strong="G1223"\w* \w faith|strong="G4102"\w*.  
\v 14 \w For|strong="G1063"\w* \w if|strong="G1487"\w* \w those|strong="G3588"\w* \w who|strong="G3588"\w* \w are|strong="G3588"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w law|strong="G3551"\w* \w are|strong="G3588"\w* \w heirs|strong="G2818"\w*, \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w faith|strong="G4102"\w* \w is|strong="G3588"\w* \w made|strong="G2758"\w* \w empty|strong="G2758"\w* \w and|strong="G2532"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w promise|strong="G1860"\w* \w has|strong="G4102"\w* \w been|strong="G2532"\w* invalidated;  
\v 15 \w because|strong="G1063"\w* \w the|strong="G1161"\w* \w law|strong="G3551"\w* \w produces|strong="G2716"\w* \w wrath|strong="G3709"\w*, \w since|strong="G1063"\w* \w where|strong="G3757"\w* \w there|strong="G1161"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w no|strong="G3756"\w* \w law|strong="G3551"\w* \w neither|strong="G3761"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w there|strong="G1161"\w* \w transgression|strong="G3847"\w*.\f + \fr 4:15 \ft How can you cross a line that is not there? So until someone draws a line (law) there is no transgression.\f*  
\v 16 \w For|strong="G1519"\w* \w this|strong="G3778"\w* \w reason|strong="G1223"\w* \w it|strong="G2532"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w faith|strong="G4102"\w* \w so|strong="G2443"\w* \w that|strong="G2443"\w* \w it|strong="G2532"\w* \w may|strong="G2532"\w* \w be|strong="G1510"\w* \w according|strong="G2596"\w* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w grace|strong="G5485"\w*, \w in|strong="G1519"\w* \w order|strong="G2443"\w* \w that|strong="G2443"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w promise|strong="G1860"\w* \w be|strong="G1510"\w* guaranteed \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w all|strong="G3956"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w seed|strong="G4690"\w*—\w not|strong="G3756"\w* \w only|strong="G3440"\w* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w those|strong="G3588"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w law|strong="G3551"\w*, \w but|strong="G2532"\w* \w also|strong="G2532"\w* \w to|strong="G1519"\w* \w those|strong="G3588"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w faith|strong="G4102"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* Abraham, \w who|strong="G3739"\w* \w is|strong="G1510"\w* \w the|strong="G2532"\w* \w father|strong="G3962"\w* \w of|strong="G1537"\w* \w us|strong="G1519"\w* \w all|strong="G3956"\w*;  
